\f0\fs24 \cf0 	Ann Harris Smith graduated from Saint Joseph College, a four-year liberal arts college for women in Emmitsburg, Maryland. It was during these years in college that she happened to attend a co-ed dance at nearby Mount Saint Mary\'92s University, where she a student, her charming, husband-to-be, Mike. It was love at first sight! The family eventually made their home in Johnstown, Pennsylvania, with their two children, Molly and Matt. Over the thirty heartwarming years of teaching kindergarten, the cups full of love and tablespoons of sunny laughs were just a few of the ingredients in an extraordinary recipe she created especially for her students of the lasting joy of reading and the gratification that comes with it. Ann is always remembered as a happy, vibrant, loving wife, mother, sister, and friend who made every person she would meet feel like they were family. Her colorful and rhythmic curriculum continues to be an integral part of elementary classrooms by using the The Color Rap Book.\\n	The Ann Harris Smith Foundation for Gynecological Cancers was created in her name to support women and their families in the region who are suffering from gynecological cancers and also to educate the community of the signs and symptoms of these diseases. Shortly after her retirement, Ann began experiencing symptoms of what doctors eventually diagnosed as stage 3C ovarian cancer. It had spread throughout her body. Fighter that she was, Ann underwent major surgery and many rounds of chemotherapy however in July 2002 at the young age of 53, she passed away. Early on her symptoms had been disregarded as signs of aging. She never wanted other women to have to go through what she did. Being an educator, she believed that making sure every women had the resources and knowledge to understand better the signs and symptoms, she, with her family, created the Ann Harris Smith Foundation. They held the inaugural Laurel Auto Group Pro-Am Charity Golf Tournament in July of 2000. This continues to this day serve as the sole fundraiser for the foundation.\\n	It was In 2014, the Smith family established a second branch of the foundation with a mission to support early childhood education. Ann\'92s influence remains with the hundreds of students she cared for throughout her teaching career. The Color Rap Book will enable Ann\'92s legacy to continue by reaching as many classrooms as possible, supporting learning for the very young, and facilitating The Color Rap Reading Program.\\n \\n	
